			<title>News High-tech methods behind massive theft of Jeep, Dodge cars</title>
			<link>http://www.graffe.com/forums/showthread.php?78901-High-tech-methods-behind-massive-theft-of-Jeep-Dodge-cars&amp;goto=newpost</link>
			<pubDate>Fri, 05 Aug 2016 00:27:33 GMT</pubDate>
			<description>High-tech methods behind massive theft of Jeep, Dodge cars (http://abc13.com/automotive/hpd-high-tech-methods-behind-massive-theft/1457015/) 
 
 
---Quote--- 
HOUSTON (KTRK) -- Houston police announced the arrest of two men accused of stealing about 30 Jeep and Dodge vehicles. Authorities say they...</description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<div><a href="http://abc13.com/automotive/hpd-high-tech-methods-behind-massive-theft/1457015/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">High-tech methods behind massive theft of Jeep, Dodge cars</a><br />
<br />
<div class="bbcode_container">
	<div class="bbcode_description">Quote:</div>
	<div class="bbcode_quote printable">
		<hr />
		
			HOUSTON (KTRK) -- Houston police announced the arrest of two men accused of stealing about 30 Jeep and Dodge vehicles. Authorities say they did it by using a laptop computer.<br />
<br />
Police say they've been watching these guys for a while but were never able to catch them in the act stealing Jeeps - until last Friday.<br />
<br />
Police say Michael Arce and Jesse Zelaya stole more than 30 Jeeps in the Houston area over the last six months.<br />
<br />
And this is how they reportedly do it: Investigators say they hook up a laptop to the Jeep, with pirated software, simply turn on the SUV, and drive it off. In many cases, the Jeeps are unlocked, so they don't have to break in.<br />
<br />
Police finally found Arce and Zelaya, because back in April a person who had his Jeep stolen had surveillance video of the crime as it took place. That helped police big-time.<br />
<br />
Officers tracked down Arce and Zelaya, and started watching their every move -- and recording them.<br />
<br />
Then, last Friday, police say they caught the thieves stealing Jeeps in the Memorial area and arrested them. Arce, 24, is charged with felon in possession of a weapon, possession with intent to deliver a controlled substance and unauthorized use of a motor vehicle. Zelaya, 22, is charged with unauthorized use of a motor vehicle.<br />
<br />
The scary part about all this - there's not much you can do to protect yourself from something like this.<br />
<br />
HPD Officer Jim Woods said, &quot;No matter what you do, you have to realize, somebody has the ability and the knowledge to steal your car. They're going to be able to take it. There's not a whole lot you can do about it.&quot;<br />
<br />
Homeland Security launched their own investigation, and discovered since November 2015, more than 100 stolen Chrysler SUVs were stolen in this way, and driven across the border.<br />
<br />
It's possible these two arrested in Houston could be tied to a much larger operation.<br />
<br />
Fiat Chrysler confirms an internal investigation is underway after more than 100 of their vehicles were stolen in the Houston area.<br />
<br />
FCA spokesman Berj Alexanian explains that employees at Fiat Chrysler dealerships, independent repair facilities and locksmiths have access to databases that list the key codes that pair key fobs with the particular vehicles they open and start. The automakers believes some of those employees have sold their username and passwords to those databases to criminals.<br />
<br />
Those criminals then buy cheap generic key fobs, find a vehicle, break into it, find the vehicle's VIN number, log onto the database and boom -- they can reprogram the key fob, start the vehicle and drive away.<br />
<br />
Essentially, it is modern-day hot-wiring of a car. The automaker is asking owners to be sure their vehicles are in a secure location at night and are locked.<br />
<br />
The company issued this official statement: &quot;FCA US takes the safety and security of its customers seriously and incorporates security features in its vehicles that help to reduce the risk of unauthorized and unlawful access to vehicle systems and wireless communications.&quot;<br />
<br />
To date, FCA has NOT been able to identify any employees who may be selling their database access to criminals.
			
		<hr />
	</div>
</div></div>

